<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry"=
>geometry</a>, a <b>rhombus</b> (<abbr title=3D"plural">pl.</abbr>: <b>rhom=
bi</b> or <b>rhombuses</b>) is an <b>equilateral quadrilateral</b>, a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrilateral" title=3D"Quadrilateral">=
quadrilateral</a> whose four sides all have the same length. Other names fo=
r rhombus include <i><b>diamond</b></i>, <i><b>lozenge</b></i>, and <i><b>c=
alisson</b></i>.
</p><p>Every rhombus is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_p=
olygon" title=3D"Simple polygon">simple polygon</a> (having no self-interse=
ctions). A rhombus is a special case of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Parallelogram" title=3D"Parallelogram">parallelogram</a> and a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)" title=3D"Kite (geomet=
ry)">kite</a>. A rhombus with right angles is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Square" title=3D"Square">square</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombus#cite_not=
e-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> A non-square rhombus has two opposite <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acute_angle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Acute angle=
">acute angles</a> and two opposite <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Obtuse_angle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Obtuse angle">obtuse angles<=
/a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2></=
div>
<p>The name <i>rhombus</i> comes from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Ancient_Greek" title=3D"Ancient Greek">Greek</a> <span title=3D"Ancient=
 Greek (to 1453)-language text"><span lang=3D"grc">=E1=BF=A5=CF=8C=CE=BC=CE=
=B2=CE=BF=CF=82</span></span> <span title=3D"Ancient Greek (to 1453)-langua=
ge romanization"><i lang=3D"grc-Latn">rh=C3=B3mbos</i></span>, meaning some=
thing that spins, such as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullro=
arer" title=3D"Bullroarer">bullroarer</a> or an ancient precursor of the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Button_whirligig" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Button whirligig">button whirligig</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombus#cite_n=
ote-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> The word was used both by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a>, who also u=
sed the term "solid rhombus" for a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Bicone" title=3D"Bicone">bicone</a>, two right circular <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cone" title=3D"Cone">cones</a> sharing a common base=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Rhombus#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A planar <i>rhombus</i> is a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_section_(geometry)" title=3D"Cro=
ss section (geometry)">cross section</a> of a bicone.
</p><p>The name <i>diamond</i> comes from the shape of an <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_octahedron" title=3D"Regular octahedron">oc=
tahedral</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diamond" title=3D"Dia=
mond">diamond</a> gemstone; the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Di=
amonds_(suit)" title=3D"Diamonds (suit)">diamonds</a> suit in <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Playing_card" title=3D"Playing card">playing ca=
rds</a> is named after the shape =E2=80=93 it was originally called <i>carr=
eaux</i> (lit. "squares") in French.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombus#cite_note-5"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> In the context of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyiamond" ti=
tle=3D"Polyiamond">polyiamonds</a>, shapes like <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Polyomino" title=3D"Polyomino">polyominos</a> but constructed=
 from equilateral triangles, a <i>diamond</i> is a rhombus with a 60=C2=B0 =
angle.
</p><p>The etymology of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lozenge=
_(shape)" title=3D"Lozenge (shape)">lozenge</a></i> is uncertain. It might =
come from a shape of some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lauzinaj=
" title=3D"Lauzinaj">lauzinaj</a> almond pastries, or from the shape of tom=
bstones. A lozenge is often specifically to a rhombus with a 45=C2=B0 angle=
.
</p><p>A <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calisson" title=3D"Cal=
isson">calisson</a></i> is a type of rhombus-shaped French sweet.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
hombus#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Characterizations">Characte=
rizations</h2></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Haltern_am_See,_Naturpark_Hohe_Mark,_Hohemark=
enbusch,_Baumstamm_--_2024_--_4411_(kreativ_2).jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a=
b/Haltern_am_See%2C_Naturpark_Hohe_Mark%2C_Hohemarkenbusch%2C_Baumstamm_--_=
2024_--_4411_%28kreativ_2%29.jpg/250px-Haltern_am_See%2C_Naturpark_Hohe_Mar=
k%2C_Hohemarkenbusch%2C_Baumstamm_--_2024_--_4411_%28kreativ_2%29.jpg" deco=
ding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"285" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-=
file-width=3D"4480" data-file-height=3D"6720"></a><figcaption>An <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intentional_camera_movement" title=3D"Intent=
ional camera movement">ICM</a> photo with a diamond-shaped composition.</fi=
gcaption></figure>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_polygon" title=3D"Simp=
le polygon">simple</a> (non-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_o=
f_self-intersecting_polygons" title=3D"List of self-intersecting polygons">=
self-intersecting</a>) quadrilateral is a rhombus <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/If_and_only_if" title=3D"If and only if">if and only if</a>=
 it is any one of the following:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombus#cite_note-7"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Rhombus#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram" title=3D"=
Parallelogram">parallelogram</a> in which a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Diagonal" title=3D"Diagonal">diagonal</a> bisects an <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internal_and_external_angle" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Internal and external angle">interior angle</a></li>
<li>a parallelogram in which at least two consecutive sides are equal in le=
ngth</li>
<li>a parallelogram in which the diagonals are perpendicular (an <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthodiagonal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Orthodiagonal">orthodiagonal</a> parallelogram)</li>
<li>a quadrilateral with four sides of equal length (by definition)</li>
<li>a quadrilateral in which the diagonals are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Perpendicular" title=3D"Perpendicular">perpendicular</a> and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection" title=3D"Bisection">bise=
ct</a> each other</li>
<li>a quadrilateral in which each diagonal bisects two opposite interior an=
gles</li>
<li>a quadrilateral <i>ABCD</i> possessing a point <i>P</i> in its plane su=
ch that the four triangles <i>ABP</i>, <i>BCP</i>, <i>CDP</i>, and <i>DAP</=
i> are all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congruence_(geometry)" =
title=3D"Congruence (geometry)">congruent</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombus#cite_note-9=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup></li>
<li>a quadrilateral <i>ABCD</i> in which the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Incircle_and_excircles_of_a_triangle" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Incircle and excircles of a triangle">incircles</a> in triangles <i>AB=
C</i>, <i>BCD</i>, <i>CDA</i> and <i>DAB</i> have a common point<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
hombus#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Basic_properties">Basic pro=
perties</h2></div>
<p>Every rhombus has two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diagonal"=
 title=3D"Diagonal">diagonals</a> connecting pairs of opposite vertices, an=
d two pairs of parallel sides. Using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Congruence_(geometry)" title=3D"Congruence (geometry)">congruent</a> <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle" title=3D"Triangle">triangle=
s</a>, one can <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_proof"=
 title=3D"Mathematical proof">prove</a> that the rhombus is <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetry" title=3D"Symmetry">symmetric</a> across=
 each of these diagonals. It follows that any rhombus has the following pro=
perties:
</p>
<ul><li>Opposite <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" title=3D"A=
ngle">angles</a> of a rhombus have equal measure.</li>
<li>The two diagonals of a rhombus are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Perpendicular" title=3D"Perpendicular">perpendicular</a>; that is, a r=
hombus is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthodiagonal_quadril=
ateral" title=3D"Orthodiagonal quadrilateral">orthodiagonal quadrilateral</=
a>.</li>
<li>Its diagonals bisect opposite angles.</li></ul>
<p>The first property implies that every rhombus is a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram" title=3D"Parallelogram">parallelogram</a=
>. A rhombus therefore has all of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Parallelogram#Properties" title=3D"Parallelogram">properties of a paral=
lelogram</a>: for example, opposite sides are parallel; adjacent angles are=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supplementary_angles" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Supplementary angles">supplementary</a>; the two diagon=
als <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bisection" title=3D"Bisection"=
>bisect</a> one another; any line through the midpoint bisects the area; an=
d the sum of the squares of the sides equals the sum of the squares of the =
diagonals (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram_law" =
title=3D"Parallelogram law">parallelogram law</a>). Thus denoting the commo=
n side as <i>a</i> and the diagonals as <i>p</i> and <i>q</i>, in every rho=
mbus
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \displaystyle 4a^{2}=3Dp^{2}+q^{2}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
