-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:14.39ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \di=
splaystyle 4a^{2}=3Dp^{2}+q^{2}.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Not every parallelogram is a rhombus, though any parallelogram with perp=
endicular diagonals (the second property) is a rhombus. In general, any qua=
drilateral with perpendicular diagonals, one of which is a line of symmetry=
, is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kite_(geometry)" title=3D"K=
ite (geometry)">kite</a>. Every rhombus is a kite, and any quadrilateral th=
at is both a kite and parallelogram is a rhombus.
</p><p>A rhombus is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangential_q=
uadrilateral" title=3D"Tangential quadrilateral">tangential quadrilateral</=
a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mathworld_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombus#cite_note-Mathworld-11"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> That i=
s, it has an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inscribed_figure" tit=
le=3D"Inscribed figure">inscribed circle</a> that is tangent to all four si=
des.
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Rhombus1.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.=
