<ul><li>Three-dimensional analogues of a rhombus include the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bipyramid" title=3D"Bipyramid">bipyramid</a> and=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bicone" title=3D"Bicone">bico=
ne</a> as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_of_revolution"=
 title=3D"Surface of revolution">surface of revolution</a>.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"As_the_faces_of_a_polyhedro=
n">As the faces of a polyhedron</h3></div>
<p>Convex polyhedra with rhombi include the infinite set of rhombic <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zonohedron" title=3D"Zonohedron">zonohedr=
ons</a>, which can be seen as projective envelopes of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypercube" title=3D"Hypercube">hypercubes</a>.
</p>
<ul><li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombohedron" title=3D"R=
hombohedron">rhombohedron</a> (also called a rhombic hexahedron) is a three=
-dimensional figure like a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cuboid"=
 title=3D"Cuboid">cuboid</a> (also called a rectangular parallelepiped), ex=
cept that its 3 pairs of parallel faces are up to 3 types of rhombi instead=
 of rectangles.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombic_dodecahedron" titl=
e=3D"Rhombic dodecahedron">rhombic dodecahedron</a> is a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_polyhedron" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Co=
nvex polyhedron">convex polyhedron</a> with 12 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Congruence_(geometry)" title=3D"Congruence (geometry)">congrue=
nt</a> rhombi as its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Face_(geometr=
y)" title=3D"Face (geometry)">faces</a>.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombic_triacontahedron" t=
itle=3D"Rhombic triacontahedron">rhombic triacontahedron</a> is a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_polyhedron" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Convex polyhedron">convex polyhedron</a> with 30 <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_rhombus" title=3D"Golden rhombus">golden rho=
mbi</a> (rhombi whose diagonals are in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Golden_ratio" title=3D"Golden ratio">golden ratio</a>) as its face=
s.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_rhombic_triacontahed=
ron" title=3D"Great rhombic triacontahedron">great rhombic triacontahedron<=
/a> is a nonconvex <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isohedral_figur=
e" title=3D"Isohedral figure">isohedral</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Isotoxal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Isotoxal">isotoxal</a> =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyhedron" title=3D"Polyhedron">p=
olyhedron</a> with 30 intersecting rhombic faces.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombic_hexecontahedron" t=
itle=3D"Rhombic hexecontahedron">rhombic hexecontahedron</a> is a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stellation" title=3D"Stellation">stellati=
on</a> of the rhombic triacontahedron. It is nonconvex with 60 <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_rhombus" title=3D"Golden rhombus">golde=
n rhombic</a> faces with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icosahedr=
al_symmetry" title=3D"Icosahedral symmetry">icosahedral symmetry</a>.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombic_enneacontahedron" =
title=3D"Rhombic enneacontahedron">rhombic enneacontahedron</a> is a polyhe=
dron composed of 90 rhombic faces, with three, five, or six rhombi meeting =
at each vertex. It has 60 broad rhombi and 30 slim ones.</li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombic_icosahedron" title=
=3D"Rhombic icosahedron">rhombic icosahedron</a> is a polyhedron composed o=
f 20 rhombic faces, of which three, four, or five meet at each vertex. It h=
as 10 faces on the polar axis with 10 faces following the equator.</li></ul=
>
